ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Please identify the aspect of your cultural background that is most central or important to you
How important is this aspect of your cultural background? - 1st Aspect
Notes: 1= Not at all important; 3= Somewhat important; 5= Very important

ElementDescription: Please identify the 2nd aspect of your cultural background that is most central or important to you
How important is this aspect of your cultural background? - 2nd Aspect
Notes: 1= Not at all important; 3= Somewhat important; 5= Very important

ElementDescription: Please identify the 3rd aspect of your cultural background that is most central or important to you
How important is this aspect of your cultural background? - 3rd Aspect
Notes: 1= Not at all important; 3= Somewhat important; 5= Very important

ElementDescription: Cultural Humility Scale (CHS) - Positive Subscale
Notes: Sum of items chs1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 12; higher scores indicate higher cultural humility

ElementDescription: Cultural Humility Scale (CHS) - Negative Subscale
Notes: Sum of reverse-coded items chs3, 6, 8, 10, 11; higher scores indicate higher cultural humility

ElementDescription: Cultural Humility Scale (CHS) - Total Score
Notes: Sum of items chs1-2, 3 (reverse), 4-5, 6 (reverse), 7, 8 (reverse), 9, 10-11 (reverse), 12; higher scores indicate higher cultural humility
